from typing import List

class Solution:
    def search(self, nums: List[int], target: int) -> bool:
        left, right = 0, len(nums) - 1

        while left <= right:
            mid = (left + right) // 2

            # Handle duplicates
            if nums[left] == nums[mid] == nums[right]:
                # We can't determine which side is sorted, so we move the left and right pointers inward
                left += 1
                right -= 1
            elif nums[mid] >= nums[left]:
                # Left half is sorted
                if nums[left] <= target < nums[mid]:
                    right = mid - 1
                else:
                    left = mid + 1
            else:
                # Right half is sorted
                if nums[mid] < target <= nums[right]:
                    left = mid + 1
                else:
                    right = mid - 1

        return left <= right and nums[left] == target
```

### Explanation:

This solution is an optimized version of the search in a rotated sorted array with duplicates. The key idea is to handle the case where there are duplicates by moving the pointers inward when the left and right elements are equal to the middle element. This is because when there are duplicates, it's not possible to determine which side of the array is sorted, so we can't directly apply the same logic as in the case without duplicates.

### Time Complexity:

- In the worst case (when all elements are the same), the time complexity is **O(n)**, because we might have to check every element.
- In the average case, the time complexity is **O(log n)**, similar to the standard rotated sorted array search.

### Follow-up:

Yes, the presence of duplicates affects the runtime complexity. In the worst case (when all elements are the same), the algorithm cannot determine which side of the array is sorted, so it has to check each element, leading to **O(n)** time complexity. Without duplicates, the algorithm can always determine which side is sorted, leading to **O(log n)** time complexity.

